Elwina says, “Children’s literature as a subject of study is hinged on multiple interdisciplinary and descriptive approaches to effectively understand the field. Its research themes provide a multifarious ways to present findings, combine insights, suggest a new direction for a given topic, and draw connections, coherently building on the available knowledges about child development.

“Hence the children’s literature becomes an educational significant aspect, which is beneficial to the child. Besides being a vehicle for enlightenment the children’s literature also creates an avenue in which parents try to intervene to facilitate and enhance their children‟s learning process. Therefore, it can explain why central ground for any family and its grown up children is inadvertently adapted to children‟s does readings (Communication, 2007: 94).

This literature work is valuable to myself and others in many ways. As an author and teacher of young children, I have acquired a set of tools that has helped me to better understand what I was experiencing and some ways I could cope with the stress and disappointment. I can comfortably stand and say that personally and professionally, the insight I gained from this study have backed and benefit people I have encountered each and every day with their specific needs.
